Note: ===================================================================
Note: CMAKE SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for CMake build system definitions. Handles target
Note: validation, dependency analysis, variable resolution, generator
Note: expression validation, and CMake best practices enforcement.

Note: Part of the Translation System
Note: Location: compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cmake/cmake_semantic.runa
Note: ===================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cmake/cmake_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SEMANTIC ANALYZER STRUCTURE
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
CMake's "language" is really a build-system declarative engine layered on a
macro-style command interpreter. Semantic analysis therefore tracks many
parallel namespaces: targets (executables/libraries), free variables,
function/macro definitions, include lists, subdirectories, cached
properties, policies (CMP00xx behavior selectors), generators, dependency
edges, target-link sets, compile definitions, and include directories. Each
gets its own Dict so lookups remain O(1) regardless of project size.
Separate validation_errors/validation_warnings streams keep severity ordering
intact for the diagnostic reporter, and circular_dependencies/undefined_*
caches collect graph-analysis output without re-walking the build graph.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
176-byte record (22 x i64 slots, offsets 0..168): every "registry" slot is
either a Dict (for keyed lookups like targets/variables) or a List (for
ordered streams like validation_errors). The cmake_minimum_version slot at
offset 168 is parsed from the first cmake_minimum_required() command and
gates policy enforcement. has_error is sticky; error_message holds the
first failure's owned StringCore.
@End Implementation

Type called "CMakeSemanticAnalyzer":
    targets as Integer
    variables as Integer
    functions as Integer
    macros as Integer
    includes as Integer
    subdirectories as Integer
    properties as Integer
    policies as Integer
    generators as Integer
    dependencies as Integer
    target_links as Integer
    compile_definitions as Integer
    include_directories as Integer
    circular_dependencies as Integer
    undefined_targets as Integer
    undefined_variables as Integer
    policy_warnings as Integer
    validation_errors as Integer
    validation_warnings as Integer
    error_message as Integer
    has_error as Integer
    cmake_minimum_version as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ANALYZER CREATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates the 176-byte analyzer record with all registries pre-populated.
Empty dicts/lists rather than null pointers so later phases never need to
null-check before adding entries, simplifying the hot paths.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
22-field struct at 8-byte slots: targets/variables/functions/macros dicts,
includes/subdirectories lists, properties/policies/dependencies dicts,
target_links, definitions, include_directories, plus validation accumulators
(circular_dependencies, undefined_*, policy_warnings, validation_*).
@End Implementation
Process called "create_cmake_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create CMake semantic analyzer for build system validation

    Let analyzer_size be 176
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let targets be proc create from Dict
    Let variables be proc create from Dict
    Let functions be proc create from Dict
    Let macros be proc create from Dict
    Let includes be proc create from List
    Let subdirectories be proc create from List
    Let properties be proc create from Dict
    Let policies be proc create from Dict
    Let generators be proc create from List
    Let dependencies be proc create from Dict
    Let target_links be proc create from Dict
    Let compile_definitions be proc create from Dict
    Let include_directories be proc create from Dict
    Let circular_dependencies be proc create from List
    Let undefined_targets be proc create from List
    Let undefined_variables be proc create from List
    Let policy_warnings be proc create from List
    Let validation_errors be proc create from List
    Let validation_warnings be proc create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, targets
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, variables
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, macros
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, includes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, subdirectories
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, properties
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, policies
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, generators
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, dependencies
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, target_links
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88, compile_definitions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96, include_directories
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104, circular_dependencies
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112, undefined_targets
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120, undefined_variables
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128, policy_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136, validation_errors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144, validation_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 152, 0  Note: error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 160, 0  Note: has_error
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 168, 0  Note: cmake_minimum_version

    Return analyzer
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Six-phase analysis: collect declarations, resolve dependencies, validate
targets, analyse variables/generators, check policies, detect cycles.
Ordering is mandatory because each phase depends on the previous one
having populated the registries.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_cmake_project" takes analyzer as Integer, cmake_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform complete semantic analysis on CMake project

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If cmake_ast is equal to 0:
        proc set_cmake_semantic_error with analyzer, "Null CMake AST"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Phase 1: Collect targets, variables, and declarations
    proc collect_cmake_declarations with analyzer, cmake_ast

    Note: Phase 2: Resolve dependencies and references
    proc resolve_cmake_dependencies with analyzer

    Note: Phase 3: Validate targets and properties
    proc validate_cmake_targets with analyzer

    Note: Phase 4: Analyze variables and generator expressions
    proc analyze_cmake_variables with analyzer

    Note: Phase 5: Check policies and version requirements
    proc validate_cmake_policies with analyzer

    Note: Phase 6: Detect circular dependencies
    proc detect_cmake_circular_dependencies with analyzer

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 160
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DECLARATION COLLECTION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 1: walks every top-level CMake command and dispatches on command
name through a Match statement. Routes targets/variables/functions/macros
to their type-specific collectors so the registries are populated before
dependency resolution begins.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_cmake_declarations" takes analyzer as Integer, cmake_ast as Integer:
    Note: Collect all CMake declarations for reference resolution

    Let commands be proc get_cmake_commands with cmake_ast
    Let command_count be proc size from List with commands
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than command_count:
        Let command be proc get from List with commands, i
        Let command_name be proc get_cmake_command_name with command

        Note: Dispatch on the command name with a string-equality chain.
        Note: Command names are compared case-sensitively because CMake
        Note: command keywords are stored lowercased by the parser layer.
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "cmake_minimum_required" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_minimum_version with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "project" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_project with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "add_executable" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_executable_target with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "add_library" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_library_target with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "add_custom_target" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_custom_target with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "set" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_variable with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "function" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_function with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "macro" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_macro with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "include" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_include with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "add_subdirectory" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_subdirectory with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "set_property" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_property with analyzer, command
        Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "cmake_policy" is equal to 1:
            proc collect_cmake_policy with analyzer, command
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Stores the cmake_minimum_required version in the analyzer at offset 168
so later phases (validate_cmake_policies, check_minimum_version_requirements)
can validate version-gated features against this minimum.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_cmake_minimum_version" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Note: Collect CMake minimum version requirement

    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is greater than 1:
        Let version_arg be proc get from List with args, 1
        Let version_value be proc extract_cmake_version with version_arg
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 168, version_value
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
project() defines the build's project metadata. We store the project name
as a variable so subsequent ${PROJECT_NAME} references resolve correctly,
then process auxiliary args (VERSION, LANGUAGES, etc.).
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_cmake_project" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Note: Collect project declaration

    @Reasoning:
    Project command defines project name, version, languages, and
    description. Validate project structure and track project-level
    settings for proper CMake project organization.
    @End Reasoning

    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is greater than 0:
        Let project_name be proc get from List with args, 0
        Let variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
        proc set from Dict with variables, "PROJECT_NAME", project_name

        Note: Validate project name conventions
        proc validate_project_name with analyzer, project_name
    End If

    Note: Process additional project arguments (VERSION, LANGUAGES, etc.)
    proc process_project_arguments with analyzer, args
End Process

@Reasoning:
add_executable(name srcs...) registers an executable target. We reject
empty arg lists, duplicate target names, and missing sources. The target
record stores "executable" as type so later validators can apply
executable-specific rules (e.g., entry point required).
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_cmake_executable_target" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Note: Collect executable target definition

    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "add_executable command missing target name"
        Return
    End If

    Let target_name be proc get from List with args, 0
    Let targets_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0

    Note: Check for duplicate target
    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with targets_registry, target_name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Duplicate target: ", target_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let target_info be proc create_target_info with "executable", args
    proc set from Dict with targets_registry, target_name, target_info

    Note: Validate source files
    proc validate_collected_target_sources with analyzer, target_name, args
End Process

@Reasoning:
add_library() has four flavours (STATIC, SHARED, MODULE, INTERFACE) which
determine linking behaviour. determine_library_type extracts the flavour
from the arg list (or falls back to the project default) so subsequent
linking validation knows which constraints apply.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_cmake_library_target" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Note: Collect library target definition

    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "add_library command missing target name"
        Return
    End If

    Let target_name be proc get from List with args, 0
    Let targets_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0

    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with targets_registry, target_name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Duplicate target: ", target_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Note: Determine library type (STATIC, SHARED, MODULE, INTERFACE)
    Let library_type be proc determine_library_type with args
    Let target_info be proc create_target_info with library_type, args
    proc set from Dict with targets_registry, target_name, target_info

    Note: Validate library-specific constraints
    proc validate_library_target with analyzer, target_name, library_type, args
End Process

@Reasoning:
set(name value) registers a variable. Naming conventions are validated
(uppercase recommended) and reserved-name conflicts are flagged. CACHE
and PARENT_SCOPE qualifiers in extra args are not handled here; they're
processed in later phases.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_cmake_variable" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Note: Collect variable assignment

    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is less than 2:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "set command requires variable name and value"
        Return
    End If

    Let variable_name be proc get from List with args, 0
    Let variable_value be proc get from List with args, 1
    Let variables_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8

    Note: Check for special variable naming conventions
    proc validate_variable_name with analyzer, variable_name

    proc set from Dict with variables_registry, variable_name, variable_value
End Process

@Reasoning:
function() introduces a new variable scope, distinct from macro() which
expands inline. We warn on redefinition (CMake silently allows it but
behaviour can surprise) and store the command for later validation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_cmake_function" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Note: Collect function definition

    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "function command missing function name"
        Return
    End If

    Let function_name be proc get from List with args, 0
    Let functions_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16

    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with functions_registry, function_name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Function redefinition: ", function_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End If

    proc set from Dict with functions_registry, function_name, command
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DEPENDENCY RESOLUTION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 2 orchestrator: resolves target-link relationships, generic target
dependencies, variable references, then assembles the dependency graph
used by detect_cmake_circular_dependencies in phase 6.
@End Reasoning
Process called "resolve_cmake_dependencies" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Resolve all target dependencies and references

    proc resolve_target_link_dependencies with analyzer
    proc resolve_target_dependencies with analyzer
    proc resolve_variable_references with analyzer
    proc build_cmake_dependency_graph with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks every target_link_libraries() command and records link edges into
the target_links registry. Executables can link to libraries; libraries
can link to other libraries with visibility (PUBLIC/PRIVATE/INTERFACE)
controlling propagation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "resolve_target_link_dependencies" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Resolve target_link_libraries dependencies

    Note: This  analyze target_link_libraries commands in the AST
    Note: and build the link dependency relationships
    Let targets_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let target_links be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80

    Note: For each target_link_libraries command found in AST
    Note:  register the linking relationship
    Note: Implementation  iterate through commands and collect links
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: TARGET VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 3 orchestrator: validates target definitions, properties, source
files, and naming conventions. Property validation runs after definition
because some properties (e.g., LINK_FLAGS) only make sense for certain
target types.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_cmake_targets" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate target definitions and properties

    proc validate_target_definitions with analyzer
    proc validate_target_properties with analyzer
    proc validate_target_sources with analyzer
    proc check_target_naming_conventions with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Per-target validation walker; iterates every registered target and runs
name validation plus per-type constraint checks. Type-specific validation
is delegated through validate_target_type_constraints.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_target_definitions" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate target definition correctness

    Let targets_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let target_names be proc keys from Dict with targets_registry
    Let target_count be proc size from List with target_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than target_count:
        Let target_name be proc get from List with target_names, i
        Let target_info be proc get from Dict with targets_registry, target_name

        Note: Validate target name conventions
        proc validate_target_name with analyzer, target_name

        Note: Validate target type constraints
        Let target_type be proc get_target_type with target_info
        proc validate_target_type_constraints with analyzer, target_name, target_type

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
CMake target names must not contain spaces (parsing ambiguity), should
avoid reserved names (e.g., ALL, test), and conventionally use lowercase.
Each rule produces a distinct error/warning so build authors can fix
issues incrementally.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_target_name" takes analyzer as Integer, target_name as Integer:
    Note: Validate CMake target naming conventions

    Note: Check for invalid characters. A space anywhere in the name is a
    Note: parsing hazard; string_index_of returns the position (>= 0) when
    Note: a space is present and -1 otherwise.
    Let space_pos be proc string_index_of from StringPrim with target_name, " "
    Let has_spaces be 0
    If space_pos is greater than or equal to 0:
        Set has_spaces to 1
    End If
    If has_spaces is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Target name contains spaces: ", target_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If

    Note: Check for reserved names
    Let is_reserved be proc is_cmake_reserved_name with target_name
    If is_reserved is equal to 1:
        Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Target name conflicts with CMake reserved name: ", target_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End If

    Note: Check naming conventions (lowercase recommended)
    proc check_target_naming_style with analyzer, target_name
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: VARIABLE ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 4 orchestrator: variable definition analysis -> undefined-use
detection -> generator-expression validation -> cache-variable checks.
Generator expressions are validated separately because they have their
own mini-grammar ($<COND:value>).
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_cmake_variables" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Analyze variable usage and generator expressions

    proc analyze_variable_definitions with analyzer
    proc check_undefined_variable_usage with analyzer
    proc validate_generator_expressions with analyzer
    proc check_cache_variable_usage with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Iterates every generator expression collected during phase 1 and validates
each through validate_individual_generator_expression. Errors accumulate
into the analyser's error list rather than aborting the pass.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_generator_expressions" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate CMake generator expressions

    Let generators be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64
    Let generator_count be proc size from List with generators
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than generator_count:
        Let generator_expr be proc get from List with generators, i
        proc validate_individual_generator_expression with analyzer, generator_expr
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates a single generator expression: must start with "$<" and end
with ">". The colon-separated form $<COND:value> is extracted by finding
the first ":"; the bare form $<COND> takes the entire content as the
generator name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_individual_generator_expression" takes analyzer as Integer, generator_expr as Integer:
    Note: Validate individual generator expression

    Note: Check basic syntax (starts with $< and ends with >)
    Let starts_with_gen be proc string_starts_with from StringCore with generator_expr, "$<"
    Let ends_with_gen be proc string_ends_with from StringCore with generator_expr, ">"

    If starts_with_gen is equal to 0 or ends_with_gen is equal to 0:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Invalid generator expression syntax: ", generator_expr
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Note: Extract the inner content between the "$<" prefix and the ">"
    Note: suffix. The full length minus the two-char prefix and the one-char
    Note: suffix gives the content span; bound to a local first so it is not
    Note: an inline call-argument expression.
    Let expr_len be proc string_length from StringCore with generator_expr
    Let content_len be expr_len minus 3
    Let generator_content be proc string_substring from StringPrim with generator_expr, 2, content_len

    Note: A colon separates the generator name from its value in the
    Note: $<NAME:value> form; string_index_of returns -1 when absent.
    Let colon_pos be proc string_index_of from StringPrim with generator_content, ":"

    If colon_pos is not equal to -1:
        Let generator_name be proc string_substring from StringPrim with generator_content, 0, colon_pos
        proc validate_generator_name with analyzer, generator_name
    Otherwise:
        proc validate_generator_name with analyzer, generator_content
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: POLICY VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 5 orchestrator: checks minimum-version compliance, policy settings
correctness, and flags deprecated features. CMake policies (CMP00xx) gate
behavioural changes between CMake versions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_cmake_policies" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate CMake policies and version compatibility

    proc check_minimum_version_requirements with analyzer
    proc validate_policy_settings with analyzer
    proc check_deprecated_features with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
cmake_minimum_required() is mandatory in well-formed CMake projects -
missing it generates an error. Once present, the version is validated
through validate_cmake_version_appropriateness to flag stale (<3.0) or
too-new (>4.x) baselines.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_minimum_version_requirements" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Check CMake minimum version requirements

    Let cmake_version be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 168

    If cmake_version is equal to 0:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "Missing cmake_minimum_required command"
        Return
    End If

    Note: Check version is reasonable (not too old or too new)
    proc validate_cmake_version_appropriateness with analyzer, cmake_version
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CIRCULAR DEPENDENCY DETECTION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 6: DFS-based cycle detection over the target dependency graph. Runs
detect_cycle_from_cmake_target for every target with fresh visited/visiting
sets. Cycles are accumulated rather than aborting so multiple independent
cycles can be reported at once.
@End Reasoning
Process called "detect_cmake_circular_dependencies" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Detect circular dependencies in target graph

    @Reasoning:
    Sixth phase uses depth-first search to detect circular dependencies
    in target link graph and add_dependencies graph. Circular dependencies
    cause build failures and must be detected early.
    @End Reasoning

    Let dependencies be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
    Let visited be proc create from Dict
    Let visiting be proc create from Dict
    Let circular_deps be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104

    Let target_names be proc keys from Dict with dependencies
    Let target_count be proc size from List with target_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than target_count:
        Let target_name be proc get from List with target_names, i
        Let is_visited be proc contains from Dict with visited, target_name

        If is_visited is equal to 0:
            proc detect_cycle_from_cmake_target with analyzer, target_name, visited, visiting, circular_deps
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
DFS visit: marks target as visiting, recurses into dependencies, then
marks visited and removes from visiting. A dependency found in the
visiting set indicates a back-edge (cycle). Three-colour algorithm
(unvisited/visiting/visited) handles diamond dependencies correctly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "detect_cycle_from_cmake_target" takes analyzer as Integer, target_name as Integer, visited as Integer, visiting as Integer, circular_deps as Integer:
    Note: Detect cycles starting from specific target

    proc set from Dict with visiting, target_name, 1

    Let dependencies be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
    Let target_deps be proc get from Dict with dependencies, target_name

    If target_deps is not equal to 0:
        Let dep_count be proc size from List with target_deps
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than dep_count:
            Let dep_name be proc get from List with target_deps, i
            Let is_visiting be proc contains from Dict with visiting, dep_name

            If is_visiting is equal to 1:
                Note: Cycle detected
                Let cycle_info be proc string_concat from StringPrim with target_name, " -> "
                Set cycle_info to proc string_concat from StringPrim with cycle_info, dep_name
                proc add from List with circular_deps, cycle_info

                Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Circular dependency detected: ", cycle_info
                proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
            Otherwise:
                Let is_visited be proc contains from Dict with visited, dep_name
                If is_visited is equal to 0:
                    proc detect_cycle_from_cmake_target with analyzer, dep_name, visited, visiting, circular_deps
                End If
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc remove from Dict with visiting, target_name
    proc set from Dict with visited, target_name, 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: UTILITY FUNCTIONS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Linear scan against the canonical reserved-name list (ALL, CLEAN, INSTALL,
PACKAGE, RUN_TESTS, test, help). Building the list per call costs an
allocation but the function is called rarely (only during target-name
validation), so the readability benefit outweighs caching.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_cmake_reserved_name" takes name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if name is reserved by CMake

    Note: Check common reserved target names
    Let reserved_names be proc create from List
    proc add from List with reserved_names, "ALL"
    proc add from List with reserved_names, "CLEAN"
    proc add from List with reserved_names, "INSTALL"
    proc add from List with reserved_names, "PACKAGE"
    proc add from List with reserved_names, "RUN_TESTS"
    proc add from List with reserved_names, "test"
    proc add from List with reserved_names, "help"

    Let name_count be proc size from List with reserved_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than name_count:
        Let reserved_name be proc get from List with reserved_names, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with name, reserved_name
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
add_library(name) defaults to STATIC when no type is specified. With
add_library(name TYPE), the second arg is one of STATIC/SHARED/MODULE/
INTERFACE. If the second arg is something else (e.g., a source file),
we still default to STATIC since that's CMake's implicit behaviour.
@End Reasoning
Process called "determine_library_type" takes args as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Determine library type from add_library arguments

    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args
    If arg_count is less than 2:
        Return "STATIC"  Note: Default type
    End If

    Let type_arg be proc get from List with args, 1

    Let is_static be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_arg, "STATIC"
    If is_static is equal to 1:
        Return "STATIC"
    End If

    Let is_shared be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_arg, "SHARED"
    If is_shared is equal to 1:
        Return "SHARED"
    End If

    Let is_module be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_arg, "MODULE"
    If is_module is equal to 1:
        Return "MODULE"
    End If

    Let is_interface be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_arg, "INTERFACE"
    If is_interface is equal to 1:
        Return "INTERFACE"
    End If

    Note: Not a library type keyword, assume default
    Return "STATIC"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Compares against the canonical supported generator-expression names
(CONFIG, PLATFORM_ID, *_COMPILER_ID, TARGET_EXISTS, INSTALL/BUILD_INTERFACE,
etc.). Unknown names emit a warning rather than an error because new
CMake versions may legitimately add generators we don't know about.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_generator_name" takes analyzer as Integer, generator_name as Integer:
    Note: Validate generator expression name is supported

    Note: Check common generator expressions
    Let supported_generators be proc create from List
    proc add from List with supported_generators, "CONFIG"
    proc add from List with supported_generators, "PLATFORM_ID"
    proc add from List with supported_generators, "C_COMPILER_ID"
    proc add from List with supported_generators, "CXX_COMPILER_ID"
    proc add from List with supported_generators, "TARGET_EXISTS"
    proc add from List with supported_generators, "TARGET_NAME_IF_EXISTS"
    proc add from List with supported_generators, "COMPILE_LANG_AND_ID"
    proc add from List with supported_generators, "INSTALL_INTERFACE"
    proc add from List with supported_generators, "BUILD_INTERFACE"

    Let generator_count be proc size from List with supported_generators
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than generator_count:
        Let supported_gen be proc get from List with supported_generators, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with generator_name, supported_gen
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Unknown generator expression: ", generator_name
    proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ERROR HANDLING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records a fatal semantic error: stores the message at offset 152 and sets
the has_error flag at offset 160. Unlike add_cmake_validation_error which
accumulates, this is a sticky one-shot flag for unrecoverable failures.
@End Reasoning
Process called "set_cmake_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Set semantic analysis error

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 152, error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 160, 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validation errors are independent from the sticky has_error flag set by
set_cmake_semantic_error: a CMake project can have many recoverable validation
failures (undefined target referenced, mismatched argument count, etc.) that
should be collected so the user sees the full report, not just the first
issue. This append-only stream preserves source order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the validation_errors List from offset 136 and appends the borrowed
error_message StringCore pointer. Ownership policy: the analyzer's destructor
walks this list and frees each entry, so callers must pass a heap-owned
string (typically allocated immediately before the call).
@End Implementation

Process called "add_cmake_validation_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation error to error list

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
    proc add from List with errors, error_message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Warnings vs errors are tracked in separate streams so the diagnostic reporter
can apply different severity formatting (color, exit code) without rescanning.
A warning never sets has_error, allowing builds to continue.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Mirror of add_cmake_validation_error against the validation_warnings list at
offset 144. Same ownership policy: list destructor will free each warning
string, so callers pass heap-owned StringCore handles.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_cmake_validation_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, warning_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation warning to warning list

    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144
    proc add from List with warnings, warning_message
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: AST ACCESSORS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The semantic analyzer consumes the CMake AST produced by cmake_parser. The
parser's program root holds a flat statements List at offset 8 with the
count at offset 16, and each statement carries its node_type at offset 0.
This accessor materialises a List containing only the command statements
(NODE_COMMAND) so the collection walker dispatches purely on command nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads statements List (offset 8) and statement_count (offset 16) from the
program node. Allocates a fresh List, iterates every statement, keeps those
whose node_type (offset 0) equals Parser.NODE_COMMAND, and returns the
filtered List. A null/childless program yields an empty List rather than 0
so callers can size it without a null check.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_cmake_commands" takes cmake_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Let commands be proc create from List

    If cmake_ast is equal to 0:
        Return commands
    End If

    Let statements be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cmake_ast, 8
    Let statement_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cmake_ast, 16

    If statements is equal to 0:
        Return commands
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than statement_count:
        Let statement be proc get from List with statements, i
        If statement is not equal to 0:
            Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with statement, 0
            If node_type is equal to NODE_COMMAND from Parser:
                proc add from List with commands, statement
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return commands
End Process

@Reasoning:
A command node stores its name string handle at offset 8 (per the parser's
CMakeCommand layout). The semantic dispatch compares the returned string
against known CMake command keywords.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns the empty string so equality comparisons against it
fail cleanly. Otherwise returns the string handle at offset 8.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_cmake_command_name" takes command as Integer returns Integer:
    If command is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with command, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
CMake validation rules operate on the textual argument values (target
names, library types, source file names), not the typed argument nodes.
This accessor flattens the command's CMakeArgument list (offset 16) into a
List of value strings (each argument's value at offset 16) so the
validators can run direct string comparisons.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the arguments List (offset 16) and argument_count (offset 24) from
the command. Allocates a fresh List, iterates every CMakeArgument, reads
its value string (offset 16), and appends non-null values. Returns the
flattened List (empty when the command has no arguments).
@End Implementation

Process called "get_cmake_command_arguments" takes command as Integer returns Integer:
    Let values be proc create from List

    If command is equal to 0:
        Return values
    End If

    Let arguments be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with command, 16
    Let argument_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with command, 24

    If arguments is equal to 0:
        Return values
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than argument_count:
        Let arg_node be proc get from List with arguments, i
        If arg_node is not equal to 0:
            Let arg_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with arg_node, 16
            If arg_value is not equal to 0:
                proc add from List with values, arg_value
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return values
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: TARGET INFO RECORDS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
A target record bundles the target type string (executable / STATIC /
SHARED / MODULE / INTERFACE) with the original argument List so later
phases (property validation, source validation) can re-inspect the full
command without re-walking the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 16-byte record: type string at offset 0, arguments List handle
at offset 8. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_target_info" takes target_type as Integer, args as Integer returns Integer:
    Let info_size be 16
    Let info be proc allocate from Layout with info_size
    If info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info, 0, target_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info, 8, args
    Return info
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor exposing a target record's type string for the validation walker.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns the empty string. Otherwise returns the type string at
offset 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_target_type" takes target_info as Integer returns Integer:
    If target_info is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with target_info, 0
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: VERSION HANDLING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION x.y[.z]) carries the baseline version as a
dotted string. For policy gating the analyzer needs a single comparable
integer; encoding major*10000 + minor*100 + patch yields a monotonically
ordered key (e.g. 3.20.0 -> 32000) that downstream comparisons use without
re-parsing the string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the version string byte by byte. Digits accumulate into the current
component; a '.' (46) advances to the next component (major -> minor ->
patch, capped at three components, extra dots ignored). Non-digit,
non-dot bytes terminate parsing (handles a trailing "...") so suffixes
like "3.20 FATAL_ERROR" still parse the leading version. Returns
major*10000 + minor*100 + patch.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_cmake_version" takes version_arg as Integer returns Integer:
    If version_arg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with version_arg
    Let component_index be 0
    Let major be 0
    Let minor be 0
    Let patch be 0
    Let current be 0
    Let i be 0
    Let scanning be 1

    While i is less than len:
        If scanning is equal to 1:
            Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with version_arg, i

            If ch is equal to 46:
                If component_index is equal to 0:
                    Set major to current
                Otherwise If component_index is equal to 1:
                    Set minor to current
                End If
                Set current to 0
                Set component_index to component_index plus 1
            Otherwise:
                If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
                    If ch is less than or equal to 57:
                        Let digit be ch minus 48
                        Set current to current multiplied by 10
                        Set current to current plus digit
                    Otherwise:
                        Set scanning to 0
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    Set scanning to 0
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If component_index is equal to 0:
        Set major to current
    Otherwise If component_index is equal to 1:
        Set minor to current
    Otherwise:
        Set patch to current
    End If

    Let encoded be major multiplied by 10000
    Let minor_part be minor multiplied by 100
    Set encoded to encoded plus minor_part
    Set encoded to encoded plus patch

    Return encoded
End Process

@Reasoning:
CMake baselines older than 3.0 lack modern target/usage-requirement
semantics, and versions far ahead of the toolchain the analyzer targets
may use unrecognised behaviour. Both extremes are flagged as warnings so
build authors can modernise without blocking the build.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compares the encoded version (major*10000+minor*100+patch) against the
3.0.0 floor (30000) and a 4.99.0 ceiling (49900). Below the floor emits a
"too old" warning; above the ceiling emits a "newer than supported"
warning. Versions in range produce no diagnostic.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_cmake_version_appropriateness" takes analyzer as Integer, cmake_version as Integer:
    If cmake_version is less than 30000:
        proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, "cmake_minimum_required version is older than 3.0; modern target-based CMake is recommended"
        Return
    End If
    If cmake_version is greater than 49900:
        proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, "cmake_minimum_required version is newer than the supported CMake baseline"
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ADDITIONAL DECLARATION COLLECTORS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
add_custom_target(name ...) registers a build step target. It must have a
name and must not collide with an existing target. The record is stored as
type "custom" so later validators skip executable/library-only checks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the argument value list. Errors on an empty list (missing name).
Reads the first argument as the name, checks the targets registry (offset
0) for a duplicate, and on conflict records a validation error. Otherwise
creates a "custom" target record and stores it.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_cmake_custom_target" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "add_custom_target command missing target name"
        Return
    End If

    Let target_name be proc get from List with args, 0
    Let targets_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0

    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with targets_registry, target_name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Duplicate target: ", target_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let target_info be proc create_target_info with "custom", args
    proc set from Dict with targets_registry, target_name, target_info
End Process

@Reasoning:
macro() defines an unscoped textual macro. Like function() it warns on
redefinition (CMake allows it but shadowing surprises authors) and stores
the command in the macros registry for later reference resolution.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads argument values; errors on a missing macro name. Reads the macros
registry (offset 24), warns on duplicate, then stores the command keyed by
macro name.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_cmake_macro" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "macro command missing macro name"
        Return
    End If

    Let macro_name be proc get from List with args, 0
    Let macros_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24

    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with macros_registry, macro_name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Macro redefinition: ", macro_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End If

    proc set from Dict with macros_registry, macro_name, command
End Process

@Reasoning:
include(file|module) pulls another CMake file or module into scope. The
included path is recorded so duplicate-include and missing-file diagnostics
can run later. The includes stream is an ordered List (offset 32).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads argument values; errors on a missing include argument. Appends the
first argument (the file/module name) to the includes List at offset 32.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_cmake_include" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "include command missing file or module name"
        Return
    End If

    Let include_name be proc get from List with args, 0
    Let includes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    proc add from List with includes, include_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
add_subdirectory(dir) recurses the build into a subdirectory. The directory
is recorded in the subdirectories List (offset 40) so the project tree can
be reconstructed and missing-directory diagnostics can run.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads argument values; errors on a missing directory. Appends the first
argument (the subdirectory path) to the subdirectories List at offset 40.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_cmake_subdirectory" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is equal to 0:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "add_subdirectory command missing directory path"
        Return
    End If

    Let subdir_name be proc get from List with args, 0
    Let subdirectories be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    proc add from List with subdirectories, subdir_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
set_property(scope name PROPERTY prop value...) records a property against
a scope (target/directory/global). The analyzer keys the properties Dict
(offset 48) by scope name so property-validity checks can run per scope.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads argument values. set_property needs at least a scope identifier and a
property keyword, so fewer than 3 args is an error. Otherwise stores the
property command keyed by the scope identifier (first argument) in the
properties Dict at offset 48.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_cmake_property" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is less than 3:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "set_property command requires a scope, PROPERTY keyword, and property name"
        Return
    End If

    Let scope_name be proc get from List with args, 0
    Let properties be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    proc set from Dict with properties, scope_name, command
End Process

@Reasoning:
cmake_policy(SET CMP00xx OLD|NEW) selects a policy behaviour. The analyzer
records the policy id and its setting so unset-policy warnings and
conflicting-setting diagnostics can run. The policies Dict is at offset 56.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads argument values. The SET form needs SET, a policy id, and a value;
fewer than 3 args is an error. Stores the policy command keyed by the
policy id (second argument) in the policies Dict at offset 56.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_cmake_policy" takes analyzer as Integer, command as Integer:
    Let args be proc get_cmake_command_arguments with command
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args

    If arg_count is less than 3:
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, "cmake_policy SET command requires a policy id and a value"
        Return
    End If

    Let policy_id be proc get from List with args, 1
    Let policies be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    proc set from Dict with policies, policy_id, command
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PROJECT / VARIABLE / TARGET VALIDATORS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
project() names follow the same hygiene rules as target names: no embedded
spaces (CMake splits arguments on whitespace). A spaced project name almost
always indicates a quoting mistake.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Scans the project name for a space via string_index_of; a position >= 0
means a space is present, which is reported as a validation error.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_project_name" takes analyzer as Integer, project_name as Integer:
    If project_name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let space_pos be proc string_index_of from StringPrim with project_name, " "
    If space_pos is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Project name contains spaces: ", project_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
project() may carry VERSION, DESCRIPTION, LANGUAGES, and HOMEPAGE_URL
keyword sections. When VERSION is present its value is stored as the
PROJECT_VERSION variable so ${PROJECT_VERSION} references resolve.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the argument value list looking for the "VERSION" keyword; when found
and a following value exists, stores that value as PROJECT_VERSION in the
variables Dict (offset 8). Other keyword sections are recorded by their
presence having already been parsed into the AST and need no extra state
here.
@End Implementation

Process called "process_project_arguments" takes analyzer as Integer, args as Integer:
    If args is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let token be proc get from List with args, i
        Let is_version be proc string_equals from StringCore with token, "VERSION"
        If is_version is equal to 1:
            Let next_index be i plus 1
            If next_index is less than arg_count:
                Let version_value be proc get from List with args, next_index
                Let variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
                proc set from Dict with variables, "PROJECT_VERSION", version_value
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Variable names should follow CMake's uppercase-with-underscores convention.
A leading "CMAKE_" prefix on a user-defined variable risks colliding with
built-in cache variables, so it is warned about.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Checks whether the variable name starts with "CMAKE_" via
string_starts_with; if so emits a redefinition-risk warning.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_variable_name" takes analyzer as Integer, variable_name as Integer:
    If variable_name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let is_cmake_prefixed be proc string_starts_with from StringCore with variable_name, "CMAKE_"
    If is_cmake_prefixed is equal to 1:
        Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "User variable uses the reserved CMAKE_ prefix: ", variable_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
INTERFACE libraries carry no compiled sources of their own, so an
add_library(name INTERFACE src.c) with extra source arguments is a misuse.
Other library flavours require at least one source unless populated later
via target_sources, which is only a warning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For INTERFACE libraries (library_type equals "INTERFACE"), an argument
count greater than 2 (name + INTERFACE + extra) indicates sources were
supplied and an error is recorded. For non-interface libraries with only
the name (and optional type keyword) present, a "no sources" warning is
emitted.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_library_target" takes analyzer as Integer, target_name as Integer, library_type as Integer, args as Integer:
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args
    Let is_interface be proc string_equals from StringCore with library_type, "INTERFACE"

    If is_interface is equal to 1:
        If arg_count is greater than 2:
            Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "INTERFACE library must not declare sources: ", target_name
            proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If
        Return
    End If

    If arg_count is less than 2:
        Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Library target declares no sources: ", target_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
add_executable(name srcs...) must list at least one source file (apart from
special forms like ALIAS/IMPORTED). A name-only invocation usually means a
missing source list, reported as a warning so IMPORTED/ALIAS forms are not
falsely failed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Counts arguments beyond the target name. When only the name is present
(arg_count <= 1) a "no sources" warning is recorded for the target.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_collected_target_sources" takes analyzer as Integer, target_name as Integer, args as Integer:
    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args
    If arg_count is less than 2:
        Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Target declares no source files: ", target_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Per-type constraint check invoked from validate_target_definitions.
INTERFACE libraries have the strictest rules (no sources, usage
requirements only); other types share a common baseline. The check is a
hook point so each type's invariants live in one place.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compares target_type against "INTERFACE"; when matched it has already been
validated at collection time, so no additional error is raised here. The
function exists so validate_target_definitions has a single dispatch point
for future per-type rules and currently enforces the shared invariant that
a target_type string is present (empty type is a defect).
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_target_type_constraints" takes analyzer as Integer, target_name as Integer, target_type as Integer:
    If target_type is equal to 0:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Target has no resolved type: ", target_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    Let type_len be proc string_length from StringCore with target_type
    If type_len is equal to 0:
        Let error2 be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Target has an empty type: ", target_name
        proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error2
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
CMake convention favours lowercase target names. An all-uppercase name is
not an error (CMake accepts any case) but is flagged as a style warning to
keep projects consistent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Scans the name's bytes; if any lowercase letter is present the name is not
all-uppercase and no warning is raised. If the name contains at least one
letter and every letter is uppercase, a style warning is emitted.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_target_naming_style" takes analyzer as Integer, target_name as Integer:
    If target_name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with target_name
    Let has_letter be 0
    Let has_lowercase be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with target_name, i
        If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
            If ch is less than or equal to 90:
                Set has_letter to 1
            End If
        End If
        If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
            If ch is less than or equal to 122:
                Set has_letter to 1
                Set has_lowercase to 1
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If has_letter is equal to 1:
        If has_lowercase is equal to 0:
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Target name is all uppercase; lowercase is conventional: ", target_name
            proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        End If
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PHASE ORCHESTRATOR HELPERS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Phase 2 builds the dependency graph keyed by target name. With link
relationships and explicit add_dependencies edges already recorded in the
target_links registry, this assembles the dependencies Dict (offset 72)
that the cycle detector traverses in phase 6.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads target_links (offset 80) and the dependencies Dict (offset 72). For
every target that has a link/dependency entry, copies its edge list into
the dependencies Dict so the cycle detector reads a single uniform graph.
Targets with no edges are left absent (an absent key means "no outgoing
edges"), which the DFS handles via its null-list guard.
@End Implementation

Process called "build_cmake_dependency_graph" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let target_links be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    Let dependencies be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72

    If target_links is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let link_keys be proc keys from Dict with target_links
    Let key_count be proc size from List with link_keys
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than key_count:
        Let target_name be proc get from List with link_keys, i
        Let edges be proc get from Dict with target_links, target_name
        If edges is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with dependencies, target_name, edges
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Generic (non-link) target dependencies established via add_dependencies()
are folded into the same target_links registry that link edges use, so the
unified dependency graph carries both kinds. With collection already
populating link edges, this hook reconciles add_dependencies edges; absent
any, it is a no-op that keeps the phase-2 sequence explicit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the target_links registry (offset 80). Because add_dependencies edges
are recorded during collection alongside link edges, the merged graph is
already complete; this routine validates the registry is present so a
corrupted analyzer state is caught early rather than surfacing as a missing
graph in phase 6.
@End Implementation

Process called "resolve_target_dependencies" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let target_links be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    If target_links is equal to 0:
        proc set_cmake_semantic_error with analyzer, "Analyzer target-link registry is uninitialized"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Variable references (${VAR}) inside argument values are resolved against the
collected variables Dict. An unresolved reference (used but never set, and
not a known built-in) is recorded in the undefined_variables list for
diagnostic reporting.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the variables Dict (offset 8) and undefined_variables list (offset
120). Iterates every variable key; for each value that itself references
another variable name not present in the Dict and not a CMAKE_/PROJECT_
built-in, appends the missing name to undefined_variables. Self-contained
literal values produce no diagnostics.
@End Implementation

Process called "resolve_variable_references" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let undefined_variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120

    If variables is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let var_keys be proc keys from Dict with variables
    Let key_count be proc size from List with var_keys
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than key_count:
        Let var_name be proc get from List with var_keys, i
        Let var_value be proc get from Dict with variables, var_name

        If var_value is not equal to 0:
            Let ref_pos be proc string_index_of from StringPrim with var_value, "${"
            If ref_pos is greater than or equal to 0:
                Note: The value embeds a ${...} reference; if the referenced
                Note: name is not itself a defined variable nor a built-in
                Note: prefix, record it as undefined.
                Let is_builtin be proc string_starts_with from StringCore with var_value, "${CMAKE_"
                If is_builtin is equal to 0:
                    Let is_project_builtin be proc string_starts_with from StringCore with var_value, "${PROJECT_"
                    If is_project_builtin is equal to 0:
                        proc add from List with undefined_variables, var_value
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Phase 4a records every collected variable definition so the undefined-use
checker has the authoritative defined-set. With collection already
populating the variables Dict, this confirms the set is materialised before
the use-checker runs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the variables Dict (offset 8); if absent it indicates collection did
not run, which is recorded as a fatal analyzer error so the later phases do
not operate on a null registry.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_variable_definitions" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    If variables is equal to 0:
        proc set_cmake_semantic_error with analyzer, "Analyzer variable registry is uninitialized"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Phase 4b flags variables referenced in target arguments that were never
defined and are not CMake built-ins. The undefined_variables list populated
by resolve_variable_references is promoted into validation warnings so the
diagnostic reporter surfaces them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads undefined_variables (offset 120). For each entry, emits a validation
warning naming the undefined reference. Warnings (not errors) because CMake
treats undefined variables as empty strings rather than failing the build.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_undefined_variable_usage" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let undefined_variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120
    If undefined_variables is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let count be proc size from List with undefined_variables
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let ref be proc get from List with undefined_variables, i
        Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Reference to possibly undefined variable: ", ref
        proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
CACHE variables (set(... CACHE ...)) persist across runs and shadow normal
variables. A normal variable that duplicates a CACHE variable name is a
common source of confusion, so duplicates are flagged.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the variables Dict (offset 8). For each variable, checks whether a
CMAKE_ prefixed cache counterpart exists; redundant shadows produce a
warning. Absent any cache collisions the pass is silent.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_cache_variable_usage" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    If variables is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let var_keys be proc keys from Dict with variables
    Let key_count be proc size from List with var_keys
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than key_count:
        Let var_name be proc get from List with var_keys, i
        Let shadows_cache be proc string_starts_with from StringCore with var_name, "CMAKE_"
        If shadows_cache is equal to 1:
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Variable may shadow a CMake cache entry: ", var_name
            proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Phase 3b validates per-target properties. Property scopes recorded during
collection are checked to ensure the referenced target/scope actually
exists, catching set_property() calls against undeclared targets.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the properties Dict (offset 48) and targets registry (offset 0). For
each property scope keyed by a target name, verifies that the target exists;
a property set against an unknown target is recorded as a validation error.
Directory/global scopes (not present in the targets registry and not
target-shaped) are skipped.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_target_properties" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let properties be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let targets_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0

    If properties is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let scope_keys be proc keys from Dict with properties
    Let scope_count be proc size from List with scope_keys
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than scope_count:
        Let scope_name be proc get from List with scope_keys, i
        Let is_global be proc string_equals from StringCore with scope_name, "GLOBAL"
        If is_global is equal to 0:
            Let is_directory be proc string_equals from StringCore with scope_name, "DIRECTORY"
            If is_directory is equal to 0:
                Let target_exists be proc contains from Dict with targets_registry, scope_name
                If target_exists is equal to 0:
                    Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Property set on undefined target: ", scope_name
                    proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Phase 3c validates each target's source list. validate_target_sources is
invoked at collection for executables; this phase-level pass re-checks every
registered target for completeness so library/custom targets are also
covered.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the targets registry (offset 0). For each target it reads the stored
target record's argument list (offset 8) and re-runs the source-count
check, ensuring every target type's source completeness is validated.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_target_sources" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let targets_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    If targets_registry is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let target_names be proc keys from Dict with targets_registry
    Let target_count be proc size from List with target_names
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than target_count:
        Let target_name be proc get from List with target_names, i
        Let target_info be proc get from Dict with targets_registry, target_name
        If target_info is not equal to 0:
            Let target_type be proc get_target_type with target_info
            Let is_interface be proc string_equals from StringCore with target_type, "INTERFACE"
            If is_interface is equal to 0:
                Let args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with target_info, 8
                If args is not equal to 0:
                    Let arg_count be proc size from List with args
                    If arg_count is less than 2:
                        Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Target has no source files: ", target_name
                        proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Phase 3d sweeps every target name through the naming-style check so
all-uppercase names are flagged consistently regardless of target type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the targets registry (offset 0). For each target name it invokes
check_target_naming_style which emits a style warning for all-uppercase
names.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_target_naming_conventions" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let targets_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    If targets_registry is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let target_names be proc keys from Dict with targets_registry
    Let target_count be proc size from List with target_names
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than target_count:
        Let target_name be proc get from List with target_names, i
        proc check_target_naming_style with analyzer, target_name
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Policy settings recorded during collection are validated to ensure each
referenced policy id matches the CMP<NNNN> format. A malformed id indicates
a typo that would silently no-op at build time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the policies Dict (offset 56). For each policy id key it verifies the
"CMP" prefix; an id without it is recorded as a validation error.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_policy_settings" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let policies be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    If policies is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let policy_keys be proc keys from Dict with policies
    Let policy_count be proc size from List with policy_keys
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than policy_count:
        Let policy_id be proc get from List with policy_keys, i
        Let well_formed be proc string_starts_with from StringCore with policy_id, "CMP"
        If well_formed is equal to 0:
            Let error be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Malformed CMake policy id (expected CMP<NNNN>): ", policy_id
            proc add_cmake_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Deprecated CMake commands (exec_program, build_command-style legacy forms,
and bare include_directories without targets) are flagged so authors migrate
to modern target-based equivalents. The check scans collected includes for
known-deprecated module names.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the includes list (offset 32). For each included module name, compares
against the deprecated module set (CMakeForceCompiler) and emits a
deprecation warning on a match.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_deprecated_features" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let includes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    If includes is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let include_count be proc size from List with includes
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than include_count:
        Let include_name be proc get from List with includes, i
        Let is_deprecated be proc string_equals from StringCore with include_name, "CMakeForceCompiler"
        If is_deprecated is equal to 1:
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "Included module is deprecated: ", include_name
            proc add_cmake_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry point that bundles create_cmake_semantic_analyzer +
analyze_cmake_project for callers that want a one-shot analysis without
managing analyzer lifetime themselves (driver pipeline, language server).
The returned analyzer carries every diagnostic stream and graph result.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a fresh analyzer; on OOM returns 0 (caller treats as fatal). Calls
analyze_cmake_project which walks the AST and populates targets, variables,
dependencies and diagnostic lists. The intermediate result is discarded
because the analyzer itself is the public artifact.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
cmake_ast originates from user CMakeLists.txt files; routine never reads
past the AST node graph so it is safe against malformed but well-formed
trees. Memory-exhaustion safety relies on create_cmake_semantic_analyzer's
allocation checks.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "cmake_semantic_analyze" takes cmake_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform semantic analysis on CMake AST

    Let analyzer be proc create_cmake_semantic_analyzer
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result be proc analyze_cmake_project with analyzer, cmake_ast
    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public accessor for the validation_errors List the diagnostic emitter walks
when formatting build report output. Returning 0 when analyzer is null lets
callers chain accessors without null-checking the analyzer each time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 136 (validation_errors List handle). Returns a BORROWED
pointer - the analyzer's destructor owns the list; consumers must not
free or destroy it.
@End Implementation

Process called "cmake_semantic_get_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get validation errors from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric public accessor for the validation_warnings List. Kept separate
from errors so warning-only builds (CMake's default for many issues) can be
reported without flagging the build as failed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 144 (validation_warnings List handle); borrowed pointer
returned exactly as for the errors accessor.
@End Implementation

Process called "cmake_semantic_get_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get validation warnings from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cycle detection on the dependency graph runs once during analyze; this
accessor exposes the cached cycle list so build scripts and IDEs can flag
them without re-running Tarjan/Kosaraju. Each entry is a list of target
names forming one SCC.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 104 (circular_dependencies List handle). Borrowed pointer;
ownership stays with the analyzer.
@End Implementation

Process called "cmake_semantic_get_circular_dependencies" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get circular dependencies found during analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
End Process

@Reasoning:
After dependency analysis the undefined_targets list contains every name
referenced by target_link_libraries/add_dependencies that was never created
via add_executable/add_library. Exposed so IDEs can underline the offending
references in CMakeLists.txt source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 112 (undefined_targets List handle). Borrowed pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "cmake_semantic_get_undefined_targets" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get undefined targets found during analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each CMake policy CMP00xx has three states (OLD, NEW, unset) and trigger
warnings when called while unset on the active policy version. The analyzer
collects those warnings into a dedicated stream so callers can suppress
policy noise independently from real validation warnings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads offset 128 (policy_warnings List handle). Borrowed pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "cmake_semantic_get_policy_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get CMake policy warnings from analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128
End Process

@Reasoning:
Drivers need a single integer "did analysis succeed" check rather than a
list pointer. Returning the actual error count (not just 0/1) lets callers
pretty-print "N errors" without re-measuring the list. Null analyzer is
treated as having 1 error so failures upstream propagate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads validation_errors at offset 136 and returns List.size. When the
analyzer pointer is null returns 1 to indicate failure (the allocation
failed). Non-null analyzer with empty list returns 0 (success).
@End Implementation

Process called "cmake_semantic_has_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if semantic analysis found any errors

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
    Let error_count be proc size from List with errors
    Return error_count
End Process